There are two explanations for why individuals conform: Social influence is the process through which individuals adopt the beliefs or actions of others in order to blend in and be accepted by a group. Normative influence: People follow the explicit or unspoken expectations or regulations of a group in order to uphold social norms and prevent unfavorable outcomes. Normative impact happens regardless of how unclear the information is. There are three elements that affect conformity: Larger groups have a tendency to have greater social impact on people. Group unanimity: People are more like to follow rules when there is agreement within the group. Group prestige: When a group is seen as having great status or respect, people are more inclined to follow its beliefs or practices. 